  {
    "page": 9,
    "block_id": "page_009:block_051",
    "block_type": "text",
    "text": "blame to obtain the previous commit, establishing an initial VIC candidate (lines 1-4). To address potential inaccuracies arising from code evolution, an iterative verification mechanism is triggered to examine the candidate’s parent commit. This verification involves a branching logic: if the vulnerable method does not exist in the parent commit, it indicates that the current commit introduced the vulnerable method, triggering the process to terminate and identify the current commit as the VIC (lines 7-9). In cases where the vulnerable method exists, an LLM performs a semantic assessment to determine if the vulnerability remains active in the parent version, using the CVE and CWE information together with the source code of the method in the parent commit. It is important to highlight that the LLM input is carefully curated to exclude the fix commit message, because the parent commit’s message is likely unrelated to the vulnerability. If the LLM determines that the method in the parent commit is not vulnerable, then the previous commit is confirmed as the VIC (lines 10-14). Otherwise, the LLM identifies the vulnerable lines in the commit. We then apply the git blame command and further LLM analysis to these lines to trace earlier commits (lines 15-20).",
    "bbox": [
      45.57899856567383,
      83.43697357177734,
      441.2690734863281,
      252.62240600585938
    ],
    "reading_order": 51,
    "column_guess": null,
    "confidence": "medium"
  },
  {
    "page": 9,
    "block_id": "page_009:block_052",
    "block_type": "text",
    "text": "3.3 Vulnerable Version Determination",
    "bbox": [
      45.827999114990234,
      261.4212646484375,
      223.97923278808594,
      274.27301025390625
    ],
    "reading_order": 52,
    "column_guess": null,
    "confidence": "medium"
  },
  {
    "page": 9,
    "block_id": "page_009:block_053",
    "block_type": "text",
    "text": "In the context of version control systems (e.g., GitHub), tags are commonly used to denote versions. Once the LLM identifies the vulnerability-inducing commit (VIC) corresponding to a given fix commit, we can determine the set of vulnerable tags by examining the tags that include the VIC but not the fix commit. However, in the real world, repositories often maintain multiple active branches (e.g., main, release-1.0 and release-2.0), and developers often propagate both VICs and fix commits across these branches through merges, cherry-picks, or manual copying. These operations result in duplicate commits, which are commits that introduce the same changes but have different commit IDs. Failure to identify all instances of duplicate fix commits or VICs can result in inaccurate reporting of vulnerable tags, leading to an underestimation or overestimation of their scope. Duplicate Commit Identification. We identify duplicate commits by comparing the content of their patches. Specifically, we compute a hash for each hunk in every commit. For a given commit, we identify all other commits that share the same hunk hashes. If the set of hunk hashes in the candidate commit is equal to, or a subset of, that of another commit, we regard them as duplicates. This enables us to track semantically equivalent changes across branches, ensuring a more comprehensive identification of commits that introduce or fix vulnerabilities. Vulnerable Tags Determination. Given a CVE, along with its associated fix commits and VICs, we analyse the git tags in the project’s repository to identify the vulnerable tags. For each fix commit and its duplicates, we collect all tags that contain these commits, labeled 𝑇 𝑓 . Similarly, for each VIC and its duplicates, we gather all the corresponding tags, 𝑇 𝑖 . The set of vulnerable tags 𝑇 𝑣 is then those tags that belong to 𝑇 𝑖 but not to 𝑇 𝑓 :",
